/*
** Installation
*/

@node INSTALL "Font4D : Installation"

System Requires:

        PovRay 2.x ( with supplied includes )
        MUI 2.x  ( works with unregistered version as well )
        OS2.x or hotter (ANY CHIPSET)

        Font4D does not mind a good graphic card as well, but that's
        optional, of course... ( TRY MERLIN (-; )

Tested on OS2.1,OS3.0 A2000/30 with ECS.

Font4D Installation:        ( this one is simple , I hope )

SETUP PART ONE:
1. A command called 'povray' has to be in path.
        eather rename your favorite version or make a link in your path.
        - example: makelink FROM c:povray TO 'device:dir/povrayieee'
          ( you can use ANY povray 2.0 compatibel version )

2. (OPTIONAL) make copy resident in your user-startup or startup-sequence.
        makes your HardDisk flash less often (-:
        - example:    resident c:copy

3. (OPTIONAL) if you want to use an external picture converter, that can deal
		with dump/qrt files, use the enviroment variable 'F4DCONV'.
		just put the complete path and name followed by all options.
		F4D calls $F4DCONV dumpfile outputfile.
		
and now ....

Unarchive FONT4D.LHA to wherever you want to have it...
                      ( or drag the Font4D-Demo Directory )
************************************************************************
! THERE ARE TWO VERSIONS (M and H) they indentical in functionality, but
    the M version requires a minimum screen height of 600 pixels.
    ( you may delete the version you don't want )

SETUP PART TWO:
Start it (enjoy the view) and click on 'Render Settings...'.
 A new window will open including a string-gadget called 'PovRay Options'.
 Change the part where it says '+linclude' 
        to '+ldirectory of your povray-includes'.
 Select 'save as default' and then SetEnv... now you are well sorted!
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Look at the examples or read the doc (AGUIDEÛ-FORMAT) if you have to...
Hey and remember, you can allways press HELP!
@endnode

/*
** Main Window...
*/

@node MAINWINDOW "Font4D : Main Window"

  @{" Help " Link MAHELP} @{" Tutorial " Link MATUTO} @{" Undo " Link MAUNDO} 

  @{" String " Link MASTRI} @{" Word " Link MAWORD} 

  @{" Load " Link MALOAD} @{" Merge " Link MAMERG} @{" Save " Link MASAVE} 

  @{" Predefined " Link MAPRED}  @{" Total Frames " Link MATOTA} @{" Selected " Link MASELE} 

                 @{" Add  " Link MAADD} 
                 @{" Edit " Link MAEDIT} 
                 @{" New  " Link MANEW} 
                 ------
                 @{"  Up  " Link MAUP} 
                 @{" Down " Link MADOWN} 
                 @{"Delete" Link MADELE} 
                 @{"Clear " Link MACLEA} 

  @{" Start " Link MASTAR} @{" End " Link MAEND} @{" Step " Link MASTEP} 

  @{" Set Range... " Link MASETR} @{" Render Settings... " Link MAREND} @{" View Frame " Link MAVIEW} 

  @{" Generate " Link MAGENE} @{" Check " Link MACHEC} @{" Execute " Link MAEXEC} 


@Endnode

@node MAHELP "Font4D : Main Window - Help"
Clicking on this Button will bring up an layout oriented list 
of available help topics for this window.
NOTE: Font4D supports the HELP - key! 
Moving the mouse-pointer above an gadget & pressing 'HELP' will 
give you information about this gadget!
@Endnode

@node MATUTO "Font4D : Main Window - Tutorial"
This Button will start the online tutorial for font4D.
@Endnode

@node MAUNDO "Font4D : Main Window - Undo"
If you press this Button, the last changes made in the main window, will be
undone. 
Clicking again will redo the last change!
@Endnode

@node MASTRI "Font4D : Main Window - String"
Whatever you type into this String Gadget, will be used as 
the text during the whole animation!
Be awair, that not all fonts support all characters!
Supported Characters:
A-Z,a-z,0-9,-+!@#$%^*()[]
Other characters are ignored and are converted to blanks...
This might result in an uncentered object.
@Endnode

@node MAWORD "Font4D : Main Window - Word Settings..."
Clicking on this Button will open the Word-Settings Subwindow.
You are able to define the look of the rendered Text, defined in the 
@{" String " Link MASTRI} 
@Endnode

@node MALOAD "Font4D : Main Window - Load"
Yes, you guessed it! Clicking here will allow you to load a previousely 
defined @{"list of View-Commands" Link MASELE}.
The current list will be overwritten!
@Endnode

@node MAMERGE "Font4D : Main Window - Merge"
This Button allows you to load a @{"list" Link MASELE} to be added to the end 
of the current list.
@Endnode

@node MASAVE "Font4D : Main Window - Save"
If you press this Button, your current @{"list of selected View-commands" Link MASELE} 
will be save to disk.
@Endnode

@node MAPRED "Font4D : Main Window - Predefined"
This list shows all available view-commands. If you double-click on one of 
the entries, it will get transfered to the bottom of the @{"selected list" Link MASELE}.
NOTE: If you can't read the full names of the view-commands displayed here, 
try making this window bigger. ( drag Lower-Left Corner of the window ).
@Endnode

@node MATOTA "Font4D : Main Window - Total Frames"
This number displayes the total number of frames ( pictures ) your current 
animation consists of. @{"Adding" Link MAADD} a view-command the the 
@{"selected list" Link MASELE}, will add to this number. 
In reverse, @{" Deleting " Link MADELE} from the selected list will reduce this number... 
Each view-command defines the number of frames it needs. This may be changed 
in the @{"View-Command-Editor" Link SUBVIEWC}.
@Endnode

@node MAADD "Font4D : Main Window - Add"
Clicking this gadget has the same effect, than double-clicking on one entry 
in the @{" predefined list " Link MAPRED}.
The entry gets added to the bottom of the @{" selected list " Link MASELE}.
@Endnode

@node MAEDIT "Font4D : Main Window - Edit"
This Button starts the @{" View-command Editor " Link SUBVIEWC} with the active 
view-command from the @{" predefined list " Link MAPRED} as argument.
@Endnode

@node MANEW "Font4D : Main Window - New"
This Button starts the @{" View-command Editor " Link SUBVIEWC} to create 
a new view-command from scratch.
This view-command will the be added to the @{" predefined list " Link MAPRED}.
@Endnode

@node MAUP "Font4D : Main Window - Up"
Moves the active entry in the @{" selected list " Link MASELE} one position upwards.
@Endnode

@node MADOWN "Font4D : Main Window - Down"
Moves the active entry in the @{" selected list " Link MASELE} one position downwards.
Endnode

@node MADELE "Font4D : Main Window - Delete"
Deletes the active entry in the @{" selected list " Link MASELE}.
Double-Clicking in the list will remove an entry as well.
@Endnode

@node MACLEA "Font4D : Main Window - Clear"
Removes all entries from the @{" selected list " Link MASELE}.
@Endnode

@node MASELE "Font4D : Main Window - Selected List"
Adding predefined or edited view-commands to this list is really 
how you define an animation in Font4D.
So, the top view-command is the first to be executed, then the second 
... and so on.
@Endnode

@node MASTAR "Font4D : Main Window - Start"
The first frame to be rendered from all available frames.

EXAMPLE: if you use 1, then Font4D will start rendering with the first
frame. If you type in 2, Font4D will start with the second and so on...

See @{" Set Range " Link MASETR} on how to edit this value. 
@Endnode
@node MAEND "Font4D : Main Window - End"
The last frame to be rendered from all available frames.
This will tell Font4D when to stop rendering Frames.

EXAMPLE: If the total number of frames states 10, then setting 
End to 10 will render all pictures upto 10 ( according to @{" START " Link MASTA} and @{" STEP " Link MASTEP} ).
If you enter 5, Font4D will stop at the fith picture...

See @{" Set Range " Link MASETR} on how to edit this value. 
@Endnode

@node MASTEP "Font4D : Main Window - Step"
The step-rate by which to render the frames from start to end.

Example: 1 -> each frame.
         2 -> each second frame.
         3 ....

See @{" Set Range " Link MASETR} on how to edit this value. 
@Endnode

@node MASETR "Font4D : Main Window - Set Range..."
This Button will open the @{" Range Settings window... " Link SUBRANGE}
In this window, you are able to manipulate @{" Start " Link MASTAR}, 
@{" End " Link MAEND} and @{" Step " Link MAEND}.
@Endnode

@node MAREND "Font4D : Main Window - Render Settings..."
This Button will open the @{" Render Settings " Link SUBREND} Window.
In this window, you are able to manipulate the Rendering of your animation.
@Endnode

@node MAVIEW "Font4D : Main Window - View Frame"
This Button open a requester, by which you can choose picture-files.
These pictures are then displayed, using the picture-viewer defined in
the @{" Render Settings " Link SUBREND}. 
@Endnode

@node MAGENE "Font4D : Main Window - Generate"
This Buttons generates 'source-code' for each frame to be rendered and an 
script-file, to be executed, to @{" render all pictures " Link MAEXEC}.
For each frame a file called FRAMEXXXX.pov will be generated. 
( with XXXX being the file-number ).
NOTE: Changing Values in Font4D does not automaticxally update these
frame files. Make sure to generate the changes before @{" executing " Link MAEXEC} the script-file.
@Endnode

@node MACHEC "Font4D : Main Window - Check"
This Button is rather an uncomplete previewer for an animation.
Originally, I added it for debugging purposes, but thought to leave it in.
Pressing the button, will generate a list of all object-positions 
during the animation, and showing it, using more.
(More must be present in SYS:UTILITIES for this to work...
If you have OS2 or higher, this should be the case...)
@Endnode

@node MAEXEC "Font4D : Main Window - Execute"
If you previousely @{" generated " Link MAGENE} all frame-files, 
pressing this button will start rendering the frames.
The generated script file will be executed in an subwindow. 
You can continue working on your animation, but pressing Generate again, 
saving any data or changing Render Settings, 
will alter the animation during rendering. (DON'T).
@Endnode

/*
**  Word Settings
*/

@node SUBWORD "Font4D : Word Settings"

@{" InfoText " Link WSINFO}
@{" Help " Link WSHELP} @{" Undo " Link WSUNDO}
@{" Load " Link WSLOAD} @{" Save " Link WSSAVE}
@{" Font " Link WSFONT}
@{" Initial Scaling " Link WSINIT}
@{" Extrusion " Link WSEXTR}
@{" Colour/Texture Cycle " Link WSCOLT}
@{" Ok " Link WSOK}@{" Cancel " Link WSCANC}
@Endnode

@node WSINFO "Font4D : Word Settings - InfoText"
If everything is fine "OK!" is displayed here.
Otherwise @{"Error-Messages" Link ERRORMSG}.
@Endnode

@node WSHELP "Font4D : Word Settings - Help"
Pressing this Button will start the online-help for this window.
NOTE: You can also get specific help for each gadget, by moving
the mouse pointer above it and then pressing 'HELP'.
@Endnode

@node WSUNDO "Font4D : Word Settings - Undo"
Every change in this window is buffered, so by pressing the UNDO button,
you can undo the changes (-:. Pressing it again redoes the changes again.
NOTE: Only one change is buffered.
@Endnode

@node WSLOAD "Font4D : Word Settings - Load"
Allows you to load previously saved word-settings.
A requester will show you all available settings.
To Load one of these settings double-click on it.
@Endnode

@node WSSAVE "Font4D : Word Settings - Save"
Asks you for a name to save the word-settings and saves them ...
@Endnode

@node WSFONT "Font4D : Word Settings - Font"
This defines the Pov-Ray font-file, to be used to generate the 
Test-Object. This file has to be located in the include directory of Pov-Ray 
and must be structured as chars.pov! At the moment only one simple font is 
available. Future releases will feature more fonts...
@Endnode

@node WSINIT "Font4D : Word Settings - Initial Scaling"
The initial Scaling defines how the object is to be scaled 
in the X and Y direction. 
EXAMPLES:  1.0 -> No change.
          -1.0 -> mirror.
           0.0 -> deletes dimension... (Not very usefull)
@Endnode

@node WSEXTR "Font4D : Word Settings - Extrusion"
@{" Length " Link WSLENG}
@{" Sections " Link WSSECT}
Transformations:
@{" Y-Rotation " Link WSYROT}
@{" X-Scaling " Link WSXSCA}
@{" Z-Scaling " Link WSZSCA}
@{" X-Translation " Link WSXTRA}
@{" Y-Translation " Link WSYTRA}

@Endnode

@node WSLENG "Font4D : Word Settings - Extrusion - Length"
Defines Extrusion to Z axis.
This could be described as the deepness of the Letters.
Good values are 10 - 100 etc.
0 is not allowed!
@Endnode

@node WSSECT "Font4D : Word Settings - Extrusion - Sections"
This function is not supported in the current Release!
It will allow you to specify the number of section the extrusion will have...
Default: one section.
@Endnode

@node WSYROT "Font4D : Word Settings - Extrusion - Y-Rotation"
Initial Rotation in Y axis per section. 
Default: one section.
@Endnode

@node WSXSCA "Font4D : Word Settings - Extrusion - X-Scaling"
This function is not supported in the current Release!
Scaling in X axis per Section.
Default: one section.
@Endnode

@node WSZSCA "Font4D : Word Settings - Extrusion - Z-Scaling"
This function is not supported in the current Release!
Scaling in Z axis per Section.
Default: one section.
@Endnode

@node WSXTRA "Font4D : Word Settings - Extrusion - X-Translation"
Translation in the x-axis per Section.
Default: one section.
@Endnode

@node WSYTRA "Font4D : Word Settings - Extrusion - Y-Translation"
Translation in the x-axis per Section.
Default: one section.
@Endnode

@node WSCOLT "Font4D : Word Settings - Colour/Texture Cycle"
With this gadget, you can cycle through three different way of defining the 
look of your object.

@{" Predefined Colours " Link WSCOLO}
@{" Predefined Textures " Link WSTEXT}
@{" Colour Value " Link Link WSCVAL}

NOTE: Only the ACTIVE one is used! You can not combine a 
colour with a texture, etc.
@Endnode

@node WSCOLO "Font4D : Word Settings - Predefined Colour"
Displayes a list of predefined Colours your Object can have.
Double-click on the one colour you want.
@Endnode

@node WSTEXT "Font4D : Word Settings - Predefined Texture"
Displayes a list of predefined Textures your Object can have.
Double-click on the one texture you want.
@Endnode

@node WSCVAL "Font4D : Word Settings - Colour Value"
In these three gadgets, you have to enter a value for
red, green and blue.

Allowed values are 0.0 to 1.0. 1.0 means full intensity!

EXAMPLES: - RGB Values -
Red = 1.0 , Green = 1.0 , Blue = 1.0 -> full White.
Red = 0.0 , Green = 1.0 , Blue = 1.0 -> full Yellow.
Red = 1.0 , Green = 0.0 , Blue = 1.0 -> full Purpul.
Red = 0.5 , Green = 0.5 , Blue = 0.5 -> medium Grey.

TIP: Screen colours are defined in RGB as well! Look at
the Amiga Palette Programm, The values there range from 0 to 15...
@Endnode

@node WSOK "Font4D : Word Settings - Ok"
Pressing this Button will close this window, and accept all changes.
@Endnode

@node WSCANC "Font4D : Word Settings - Cancel"
Pressing this Button will close this window, and abandom all changes.
( Using the Window-Close Gadget (top left corner) has the same effect ).
@Endnode

/*
** View-Command Editor.
*/

@node SUBVIEWC "Font4D : View-Command Editor"
@{" InfoText " Link VEINFO }
@{" Help " Link VEHELP } @{" Undo " Link VEUNDO }
@{" Load " Link VELOAd } @{" ReLoad " Link VERELO } @{" Save " Link VESAVE }
@{" Name " Link VENAME }
@{" Calculation Mode " Link VEMODE }
@{" Special Effect (F/X) " Link VEFX }
@{" Frames " Link VEFRAM }
@{" Lights " Link VELIGH }
@{" Edit - Cycle " Link VEEDIT }
Object:
@{" Object Movement " Link VEOMOV }
@{" Object X-Rotation " Link VEOXRO }
@{" Object Y-Rotation " Link VEOYRO }
@{" Object Z-Rotation " Link VEOZRO }
@{" Special Effect " Link VESPEC }
Camera:
@{" Camera Movement " Link VECMOV }
@{" Camera Tracking " Link VECTRA }
@{" Camera X-Rotation " Link VECXRO }
@{" Camera Y-Rotation " Link VECYRO }
@{" Camera Z-Rotation " Link VECZRO }
@{" Camera Lens Angle " Link VELENS }
Lights:
@{" Light Selector " Link VELSLI }
@{" Light Movement " Link VELMOV }
@{" Light Intensity " Link VELINT }
@{" Spotlights " Link VESPOT }
@{" Spotlight Pointing " Link VESPOI }
@{" Spotlight Radius " Link VESRAD }
@{" Spotlight Falloff " Link VESFAL }
@{" Spotlight Tightness " Link VESTIG }

@{" Ok " Link VEOK } @{" Cancel " Link VECANC }

@Endnode

@node VEINFO "Font4D : View-Command Editor - InfoText"
Look out for @{"Error-Messages" Ling ERRORMSG} displayed in this gadget.
If everything is fine "OK!" is displayed or an message regarding the last 
operation.
@Endnode

@node VEHELP "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Help"
Starts global help display for this window.

NOTE: Using the 'HELP' Button when the mouse-pointer is above a 
gadget displayes the help for this gadget.
@Endnode

@node VEUNDO "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Undo"
Pressing this Button undoes the last changes to the data displayed.
Pressing it again redoes the last change.
@Endnode

@node VELOAD "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Load"
Opens a file-requester to select a previousely saved View-Command;
and loads it (-;
@Endnode

@node VERELO "Font4D : View-Command Editor - ReLoad"
Reloads the current View-Command from Disk.
Therefore resets to last saved Values...
@Endnode

@node VESAVE "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Save"
Allows you to save the current View-Command under a new name.
@Endnode

@node VENAME "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Name"
This represents the name of the view-command you are currently working at.
Use this name wisely to discribe, what the view-command does.
Be as specific as possible... Remember 256 characters are allowed for 
filenames! SO USE THEM....
@Endnode

@node VEMODE "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Calculation Mode"
This cycle gadget lets you choose between @{"Bezier" Link Bezier}, @{"BSpline" Link BSpline} and 
@{"Absolute" Link Absolute} Calculation Modes.

Choosing one of these methods determine how points defined in the 
@{" Coordinates-Editor " Link SUBMOVE} are interpreted!
@Endnode

@node VEFX "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Special Effect"
If you tick this box, the view-command will use an external 
special effect.
Unfortunetly I have not designed any FX's yet... (-:
@Endnode

@node VEFRAM "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Frames"
This specifies the number of frames, the current view-command will take during
the animation.
See also @{" Total Number of Frames " Link MATOTA}.
@Endnode

@node VELIGH "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Lights"
This specifies the number of Lights the current view-command will include.
@Endnode

@node VEEDIT "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Edit"
With this gadget you can choose which part of the view-command
you want to edit: object, camera or lights.
@Endnode

@node VEOMOV "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Object Movement"
Pressing this button will start the @{"Coordinates Editor" Link SUBMOVE}
to edit the Object Movement Points.
@Endnode

@node VEOXRO "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Object X-Rotation"
This defines the degree of Rotation the Object will perform, during the 
available frames, in the X Axis.
@Endnode

@node VEOYRO "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Object Y-Rotation"
This defines the degree of Rotation the Object will perform, during the 
available frames, in the Y Axis.
@Endnode

@node VEOZRO "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Object Z-Rotation"
This defines the degree of Rotation the Object will perform, during the 
available frames, in the Z Axis.
@Endnode

@node VESPEC "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Object Special Effect"
This List shows the available F/X. Select one by double clicking.
If this list is disabled (grey grid), you eather deselected the
@{"F/X" Link VEFX} Checkmark, or there are just no Special Effects availabel.
@Endnode

@node VECMOV "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Camera Movement"
Pressing this button will start the @{"Coordinates Editor" Link SUBMOVE}
to edit the Camera Movement Points.
This defines where the Camera 'Looks From'.
@Endnode

@node VECTRA "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Camera Tracking"
Pressing this button will start the @{"Coordinates Editor" Link SUBMOVE}
to edit the Object Tracking Points.
Tracking defines, where the camera 'Looks At'.
@Endnode

@node VECXRO "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Camera X-Rotation"
This defines the degree of Rotation the Camera will perform, during the 
available frames, in the X Axis.
@Endnode

@node VECYRO "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Camera Y-Rotation"
This defines the degree of Rotation the Camera will perform, during the 
available frames, in the Y Axis.
@Endnode

@node VECZRO "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Camera Z-Rotation"
This defines the degree of Rotation the Camera will perform, during the 
available frames, in the Z Axis.
@Endnode

@node VELENS "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Camera Lens Angle"
Selecting one of the options displayed here, you can determine
a lens, to be used by the camera. Experiment with this, but be
carefull: A CHANGE OF LENS DURING AN ANIMATION MIGHT HAVE STRANGE EFFECTS...
@Endnode

@node VELMOV "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Light Movement"
Pressing this button will start the @{"Coordinates Editor" Link SUBMOVE}
to edit the current Light's Movement Points.
@Endnode

@node VELINT "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Light Intensity"
Here you can specify the intensity the Light will have for the
Red, Green and Blue Spectrum. A value of 1.0 means full intensity.
See also @{" Colour Values "Link WSCVAL}.
@Endnode

@node VESPOT "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Spotlights"
If you tick this Box, the current Light will change from a normal Lightsource
to a Spotlight! A Spotlight not only has a position but also a position the
'beam' @{"points" Link VESPOI}.
@Endnode

@node VESPOI "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Spotlight Pointling"
Pressing this button will start the @{"Coordinates Editor" Link SUBMOVE}
to edit the current Spotlight's Tracking Points.
This defines where the 'beam' points...
(Better point this on the object, or you won't see anything!)
@Endnode

@node VESRAD "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Spotlight Radius"
This defines the radius of the Spotlight.
@Endnode

@node VESFAL "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Spotlight Falloff"
This more or less defines the Sharpness of the Outline.
@Endnode

@node VEOK "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Ok"
Saves the view-command and closes window...
( A Requester comes up, to check wether you want to overwrite the
original... pressing cancel allows you to specify a new name.)
@Endnode

@node VECANC "Font4D : View-Command Editor - Cancel"
Well, the usual really!
Closes window and discards changes...
@Endnode

/*
** Render Settings Subwindow.
*/

@node SUBREND "Font4D : Render Settings"

@{ " InfoText " Link RSINFO }
@{ " Help " Link RSHELP } @{ " Undo " Link RSUNDO }
@{ " Load " Link RSLOAD } @{ " Save " Link RSSAVE }
@{ " Resolution " Link RSRESO }
@{ " Size Settings " Link RSSIZE }
@{ " Predefined... " Link RSPRED } @{ " Full Picture " Link RSFULL }
@{ " Virtual Size " Link RSVIRT }
@{ " X " Link RSXSIZ } @{ " Y " Link RSYSIZ }
@{ " Picture Size " Link RSPICT }
@{ " X-Start " Link RSXSTA } @{ " Y-Start " Link RSYSTA }
@{ " Width " Link RSWIDTH } @{ " Height " Link RSHEIG }
@{ " Output " Link RSOUTP }
@{ " Quality " Link RSQUAL } @{ " Format " Link RSFORM }
@{ " PovRay Options " Link RSPOVR }
@{ " SetEnv " Link RSSETE } @{ " String " Link RSSTRI }
@{ " Static Background Scene " Link RSSTAT }
@{ " Scene... " Link RSSCEN } @{ " On/Off " Link RSCMSC }
@{ " Picture Viewer Command " Link RSVIEW }
@{ " Viewer... " Link RSVVIE } @{ " On/Off " Link RSCMVI }
@{ " Ok " Link RSOK } @{ " Cancel " Link RSCANC }

@Endnode

@node RSINFO "Font4D : Render Settings - InfoText"
Error messages are displayed here..
otherwise 'OK!' (-;
@Endnode

@node RSHELP "Font4D : Render Settings - Help"
Same procedure as every ... window!
Yes you can get some kind of help pressing this gadget.
@Endnode

@node RSUNDO "Font4D : Render Settings - Undo"
Undo-Redo Button.
@Endnode

@node RSLOAD "Font4D : Render Settings - Load"
Lets you load a set of previousely saved render-settings.
NOTE: PovRay-Options are only valid when using @{"SetEnv..." Link RSSETE}.
@Endnode

@node RSSAVE "Font4D : Render Settings - Save"
Lets you save the current render settings.
NOTE: Make sure the filename ends with '.RendSet'.
@Endnode

@node RSRESO "Font4D : Render Settings - Resolution"
This group of gadgets allow you to specify the picture size.
@Endnode

@node RSSIZE "Font4D : Render Settings - Size Settings"
Hmmm.... DUH!
@Endnode

@node RSPRED "Font4D : Render Settings - Predefined"
Well, a future version will have a set of predefined picture sizes 
available on pressing this button....
@Endnode

@node RSFULL "Font4D : Render Settings - Full Picture"
Pressing this button will set the the picture to full @{"virtual size" Link RSVIRT}.
@Endnode

@node RSVIRT "Font4D : Render Settings - Virtual Size"
The virtual size of the picture can be any size from 1 to ca. 65.000 pixel.
It does not directly define the size of the output-picture, but the
size of the scene window... 
Selecting a bigger size than the picture-size, will result in the picture being
a cut-out part from the real thing...
Example:

Virtual Size
 +----------------+---------------+-----+ X
 |                |               |     |
 |              Y-Start           |     |  
 |                |               |     |
 +----X-Start-----+ - - - - - - - +-----+--
 |                   Picture            |  ^
 |                |  Size         |     |  Height
 |                                      |  v
 +----------------+ - - - - - - - +-----+--
 |                |               |     | 
 |                |               |     |
 +----------------+---------------+-----+
 Y                | <-  Width  -> |

@{"Full Picture" Link RSFULL} will make Virtual Size = Picture Size.

@Endnode

@node RSXSIZ "Font4D : Render Settings - Virtual Size - X"
Virtual size in x direction.
@Endnode

@node RSYSIZ "Font4D : Render Settings - Virtual Size - Y"
Virtual size in y direction.
@Endnode

@node RSPICT "Font4D : Render Settings - Picture Size"
Part of the virtual size to make up the output-picture 
 ( and resolution ). 
@Endnode

@node RSXSTA "Font4D : Render Settings - Picture Size - X-Start"
Start of Picture on virtual X - Axis.
@Endnode

@node RSYSTA "Font4D : Render Settings - Picture Size - Y-Start"
Start of Picture on virtual Y - Axis.
@Endnode

@node RSWIDTH "Font4D : Render Settings - Picture Size - Width"
Width  of picture. 
( X-End = X-Start + Width ).
@Endnode

@node RSHEIG "Font4D : Render Settings - Picture Size - Height"
Height of Picture.
( Y-End = Y-Start + Height ).
@Endnode

@node RSOUTP "Font4D : Render Settings - Output"
These two gadgets define the picture @{"quality" Link RSQUAL} and @{"format" Link RSFORM}.
@Endnode

@node RSQUAL "Font4D : Render Settings - Output Quality"

Here you can choose a quality from 0 (worst but fastest) 
                                to 9 (best  but slowest).

A picture with -9- quality is roughly 10 times slower than with
quality set to -0-. So test it on -0- first...
@Endnode

@node RSFORM "Font4D : Render Settings - Output Format"
Here you may select between different picture formats...

- for IFF 24 to work, you need dump2i24 (should be included with this archive).
- for External to work, you have to set up an enviroment variable call F4DCONV 
  including: path/name options of you converter... (why not an ADPRO script ?)
  Font-4D will call this with inputfilename followed by outputfilename.

  If you haven't set up the enviroment variable. the execution of the script 
  file will stop after the first picture. "$F4DCONV unknown command".... 
  be warned (-;.
@Endnode

@node RSPOVR "Font4D : Render Settings - PovRay Options"
Have a look at the Pov-Ray Documentation for setting extra options:
    Font-4D sets tzhe following options:
    -qX -HXXX -WXXX -SCXXX -SRXXX -ECXXX -ERXXX -fX -o... -i....
	BUT, YOU HAVE TO SET +l"povray-path/include" !!!!
	See @{"SetEnv" Link RSETE} and @{"String" Link RSSTRI} on how to do this.
@Endnode

@node RSSETE "Font4D : Render Settings - PovRay Options - SetEnv"
Pressing this button overwrites the current pov-ray options with the
one in the @{" String " Link RSSTRI}.

NOTE: Loading a set of Render-Setting changes the string, but does not set
the Enviroment variable automaticly.
@Endnode

@node RSSTRI "Font4D : Render Settings - PovRay Options - String"
This string has to contain +l"povray-path/include" for Font4D to work.
otherwise povray will not find it's includes...

Other useful parameters to enter here are i.e.:
-BXXX specifieng a Buffer for the rendered picture ( speeds up rendering )
-Dx   which displayes the picture during rendering. ( please consult your
      povray documentation on which modes are supported!!!).

remember that you may not use one of the following:
    -qX -HXXX -WXXX -SCXXX -SRXXX -ECXXX -ERXXX -fX -o... -i....
    THESE ARE SET BY FONT-4D!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
@Endnode

@node RSSTAT "Font4D : Render Settings - Static Background Scene"
One of the goodies of the program for Pov-Ray - Specialists!!!

Just specify a filename in the string ( using the Scene-button )
and it will included autometicly as a stable background scene.

You can en-disable this by using the checkmark on the left of 
the string-gadget.

Soon you will be able to fly through them.....

NOTE: NO CAMERA SHOULD BE PRESENT IN THE SCENE-FILE...
You can use the original settings in the word-subwindow, or
in your view-commands. Additional lights won't be affected,
but why not have nice effects by moving them.... ????
@Endnode

@node RSSCEN "Font4D : Render Settings - Scene Button"
Well, using a filerequester, you can select a a scene.
@Endnode

@node RSVIEW "Font4D : Render Settings - Picture Viewer"
Specify a programm that is able to read your output-picture.
@Endnode

@node RSVVIE "Font4D : Render Settings - Viewer Button"
@Endnode

@node RSCMSC "Font4D : Render Settings - Scene On/Off Checkmark"
@Endnode

@node RSCMVI "Font4D : Render Settings - Viewer On/Off Checkmark"
@Endnode

@node RSOK "Font4D : Render Settings - Ok"
@Endnode

@node RSCANC "Font4D : Render Settings - Cancel"
@Endnode

